# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pressure-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A **barometer** is a scientific instrument that is used to measure air pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Pressure tendency, which is derived from barometric readings, can forecast short term changes in the weather.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Many measurements of air pressure are used within surface weather analysis to help find surface troughs, pressure systems and frontal boundaries.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Barometers and pressure altimeters (the most basic and common type of altimeter) are essentially the same instrument, but used for different purposes.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The average atmospheric pressure on the Earth's surface varies between 940 and 1040 hPa (mbar).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is 1013 hPa (mbar).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The word *barometer* is derived from the Ancient Greek βάρος (*báros*), meaning "weight", and μέτρον (*métron*), meaning "measure".
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Evangelista Torricelli is usually credited with inventing the barometer in 1643, although the historian W.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] French scientist and philosopher René Descartes described the design of an experiment to determine atmospheric pressure as early as 1631, but there is no evidence that he built a working barometer at that time.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In 1668, Robert Hooke's marine barometer, made by Henry Hunt, was noticed, and efforts were made to make it sea-worthy.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] On 27 July 1630, Giovanni Battista Baliani wrote a letter to Galileo Galilei explaining an experiment he had made in which a siphon, led over a hill about 21 m high, failed to work.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] When the end of the siphon was opened in a reservoir, the water level in that limb would sink to about 10 m above the reservoir.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Galileo responded with an explanation of the phenomenon: he proposed that it was the power of a vacuum that held the water up, and at a certain height the amount of water simply became too much and the force could not hold any more, like a cord that can support only so much weight.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This was a restatement of the theory of *horror vacui* ("nature abhors a vacuum"), which dates to Aristotle, and which Galileo restated as *resistenza del vacuo*.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Galileo's ideas, presented in his *Discorsi* (*Two New Sciences*), reached Rome in December 1638.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Physicists Gasparo Berti and father Raffaello Magiotti were excited by these ideas, and decided to seek a better way to attempt to produce a vacuum other than with a siphon.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Four accounts of the experiment exist, all written some years later.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] No exact date was given, but since *Two New Sciences* reached Rome in December 1638, and Berti died before January 2, 1644, science historian W.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Knowles Middleton places the event to sometime between 1639 and 1643.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Present were Berti, Magiotti, Jesuit polymath Athanasius Kircher, and Jesuit physicist Niccolò Zucchi.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In brief, Berti's experiment consisted of filling with water a long tube that had both ends plugged, then standing the tube in a basin of water.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The bottom end of the tube was opened, and water that had been inside of it poured out into the basin.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] However, only part of the water in the tube flowed out, and the level of the water inside the tube stayed at an exact level, which happened to be 10.3 m (34 ft), the same height limit Baliani had observed in the siphon.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] What was most important about this experiment was that the lowering water had left a space above it in the tube which had no intermediate contact with air to fill it up.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This seemed to suggest the possibility of a vacuum existing in the space above the water.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Evangelista Torricelli, who was Galileo's amanuensis for the last three months of his life, interpreted the results of the experiments in a novel way.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He proposed that the weight of the atmosphere, not an attracting force of the vacuum, held the water in the tube.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] It was traditionally thought, especially by the Aristotelians, that the air did not have weight; that is, that the kilometers of air above the surface of the Earth did not exert any weight on the bodies below it.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Even Galileo had accepted the weightlessness of air as a simple truth.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Torricelli proposed that rather than an attractive force of the vacuum sucking up water, air did indeed have weight, which pushed on the water, holding up a column of it.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He argued that the level that the water stayed at—c.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] 10.3 m above the water surface below—was reflective of the force of the air's weight pushing on the water in the basin, setting a limit for how far down the water level could sink in a tall, closed, water-filled tube.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He viewed the barometer as a balance—an instrument for measurement—as opposed to merely an instrument for creating a vacuum, and since he was the first to view it this way, he is traditionally considered the inventor of the barometer, in the sense in which we now use the term.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Because of rumors circulating in Torricelli's gossipy Italian neighborhood, which included that he was engaged in some form of sorcery or witchcraft, Torricelli realized he had to keep his experiment secret to avoid the risk of being arrested.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He needed to use a liquid that was heavier than water, and from his previous association and suggestions by Galileo, he deduced that by using mercury, a shorter tube could be used.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] With mercury, which is about 14 times denser than water, a tube only 80 cm was now needed, not 10.5 m.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Furthermore, Torricelli demonstrated that atmospheric pressure could support a column of mercury approximately 30 inches high.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In 1646, Blaise Pascal along with Pierre Petit, had repeated and perfected Torricelli's experiment after hearing about it from Marin Mersenne, who himself had been shown the experiment by Torricelli toward the end of 1644.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Pascal further devised an experiment to test the Aristotelian proposition that it was vapours from the liquid that filled the space in a barometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] His experiment compared water with wine, and since the latter was considered more "spiritous", the Aristotelians expected the wine to stand lower (since more vapours would mean more pushing down on the liquid column).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Pascal performed the experiment publicly, inviting the Aristotelians to predict the outcome beforehand.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The Aristotelians predicted the wine would stand lower.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] However, Pascal went even further to test the mechanical theory.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] If, as suspected by mechanical philosophers like Torricelli and Pascal, air had weight, the pressure would be less at higher altitudes.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Therefore, Pascal wrote to his brother-in-law, Florin Perier, who lived near a mountain called the Puy de Dôme, asking him to perform a crucial experiment.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Perier was to take a barometer up the Puy de Dôme and make measurements along the way of the height of the column of mercury.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He was then to compare it to measurements taken at the foot of the mountain to see if those measurements taken higher up were in fact smaller.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In September 1648, Perier carefully and meticulously carried out the experiment, and found that Pascal's predictions had been correct.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The column of mercury stood lower as the barometer was carried to a higher altitude.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The French name, *le baromètre Liègeois*, is used by some English speakers.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This name reflects the origins of many early weather glasses – the glass blowers of Liège, Belgium.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The weather ball barometer consists of a glass container with a sealed body, half filled with water.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A narrow spout connects to the body below the water level and rises above the water level.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The narrow spout is open to the atmosphere.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] When the air pressure is lower than it was at the time the body was sealed, the water level in the spout will rise above the water level in the body; when the air pressure is higher, the water level in the spout will drop below the water level in the body.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A variation of this type of barometer can be easily made at home.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A mercury barometer is an instrument used to measure atmospheric pressure in a certain location and has a vertical glass tube closed at the top sitting in an open mercury-filled basin at the bottom.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Mercury in the tube adjusts until the weight of it balances the atmospheric force exerted on the reservoir.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] High atmospheric pressure places more force on the reservoir, forcing mercury higher in the column.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Low pressure allows the mercury to drop to a lower level in the column by lowering the force placed on the reservoir.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Since higher temperature levels around the instrument will reduce the density of the mercury, the scale for reading the height of the mercury is adjusted to compensate for this effect.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The tube has to be at least as long as the amount dipping in the mercury + head space + the maximum length of the column.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Torricelli documented that the height of the mercury in a barometer changed slightly each day and concluded that this was due to the changing pressure in the atmosphere.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He wrote: "We live submerged at the bottom of an ocean of elementary air, which is known by incontestable experiments to have weight".
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Inspired by Torricelli, Otto von Guericke on 5 December 1660 found that air pressure was unusually low and predicted a storm, which occurred the next day.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The mercury barometer's design gives rise to the expression of atmospheric pressure in inches or millimeters of mercury (mmHg).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A torr was originally defined as 1 mmHg.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The pressure is quoted as the level of the mercury's height in the vertical column.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Typically, atmospheric pressure is measured between 26.5 inches (670 mm) and 31.5 inches (800 mm) of Hg.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] One atmosphere (1 atm) is equivalent to 29.92 inches (760 mm) of mercury.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Design changes to make the instrument more sensitive, simpler to read, and easier to transport resulted in variations such as the basin, siphon, wheel, cistern, Fortin, multiple folded, stereometric, and balance barometers.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In 2007, a European Union directive was enacted to restrict the use of mercury in new measuring instruments intended for the general public, effectively ending the production of new mercury barometers in Europe.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The repair and trade of antiques (produced before late 1957) remained unrestricted.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Fortin barometers use a variable displacement mercury cistern, usually constructed with a thumbscrew pressing on a leather diaphragm bottom (V in the diagram).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This compensates for displacement of mercury in the column with varying pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] To use a Fortin barometer, the level of mercury is set to zero by using the thumbscrew to make an ivory pointer (O in the diagram) just touch the surface of the mercury.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The pressure is then read on the column by adjusting the vernier scale so that the mercury just touches the sightline at Z.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Some models also employ a valve for closing the cistern, enabling the mercury column to be forced to the top of the column for transport.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This prevents water-hammer damage to the column in transit.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A sympiesometer is a compact and lightweight barometer that was widely used on ships in the early 19th century.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The sensitivity of this barometer was also used to measure altitude.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] One is a traditional mercury thermometer that is needed to calculate the expansion or contraction of the fluid in the barometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The other is the barometer, consisting of a J-shaped tube open at the lower end and closed at the top, with small reservoirs at both ends of the tube.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In 1778, Blondeau developed an iron tube barometer using narrow-bore musket barrels.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This design resulted in a durable and polished instrument that resisted mercury corrosion and minimized breakage from the ship's movement.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The need for a practical marine barometer arose from the urgent necessity of weather prediction at sea, where sailors faced frequent, and often dangerous, changes in wind, calm, and storm conditions.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Traditional mercury barometers, though useful on land, proved unreliable on ships due to their susceptibility to the ship’s motion.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Oscillations caused the mercury to strike the top of the glass tube, leading to frequent breakage and making air pressure readings nearly impossible to interpret accurately during voyages.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Roger North observed that many, including Robert Hooke, attempted to resolve these issues but often abandoned the endeavor due to technical limitations.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Nonetheless, Hooke remained persistent, proposing several adaptations including narrowing the open end of the siphon tube and exploring spiral tube designs.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] His most notable contribution was the creation of a double thermometer marine barometer, also referred to as a manometer, which was presented to the Royal Society in 1668 and constructed by Henry Hunt.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Hooke’s marine barometer marked a turning point in the development of nautical meteorological tools.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] It featured a compact, affordable design tailored for maritime use, becoming the first instrument specifically constructed for sailors.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The device combined a sealed spirit thermometer with an open air-based thermometer, calibrated to reflect barometric pressure changes through liquid displacement.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Hooke’s use of hydrogen-filled containers and colorful almond oil further enhanced visibility and responsiveness.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Notably, Edmund Halley tested this prototype on his South Atlantic voyage from 1698 to 1700 and praised its reliability in forecasting weather changes.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] His endorsement led to greater interest and validation by the Royal Society.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Figure 8 below is from this report, depicting the Hooke Barometer, with detailed description in the writing.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He consistently found it effective in forecasting storms, wind changes, and even the proximity of ice.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A significant advancement occurred during Captain James Cook’s renowned voyages in the late 18th century.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] As part of preparations for Cook’s second Pacific expedition (1772–1775), the Board of Longitude and the Royal Society commissioned the production of marine barometers.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Renowned instrument maker Edward Nairne was chosen to supply the equipment.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Contrary to expectations for spiral tubes, Nairne opted for straight, constricted tubes mounted on boards, coupled with a gimbaled suspension system to ensure vertical orientation and stability at sea.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Nairne’s design represented a leap in functionality.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The narrow bore significantly reduced mercury motion, enabling more accurate readings even in turbulent conditions.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] These instruments proved so reliable that they were adopted not only by the Royal Navy but also by international expeditions.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The East India Company, Russian explorers, and French and Spanish navigators, including Jean-François de Galaup, comte de Lapérouse (voyage in 1785) and Alessandro Malaspina (voyage in 1789), incorporated variants of Nairne’s barometer into their voyages.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Despite the widespread use of Nairne’s marine barometer, it was not without limitations.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Lapérouse lauded the device’s predictive capabilities but also noted inconsistencies in mercury behavior, highlighting the complexity of translating instrument readings into reliable forecasts.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In response to the fragility of glass tubes, other scientists, such as Le Roy, proposed alternate models like the folded Huygens barometer, designed for enhanced durability and reduced oscillation aboard ships.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The marine barometer’s practical value was reaffirmed in 1801 when the Royal Society sent Captain Matthew Flinders on a three-year voyage from New Holland to New South Wales, equipped with one of Nairne’s barometers.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In his official correspondence, Flinders confirmed the instrument’s success and expressed appreciation for its stability and precision in recording atmospheric conditions.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Throughout its evolution, the marine barometer transitioned from a theoretical invention to a critical navigational and meteorological tool.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Its development not only reflected ingenuity in overcoming the challenges of shipboard instrumentation but also underscored its importance in the broader context of global exploration.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] These devices empowered mariners to make informed decisions, contributing to safer and more efficient voyages across the world's oceans.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A wheel barometer uses a "J" tube sealed at the top of the longer limb.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The shorter limb is open to the atmosphere, and floating on top of the mercury there is a small glass float.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A fine silken thread is attached to the float which passes up over a wheel and then back down to a counterweight (usually protected in another tube).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The wheel turns the point on the front of the barometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] As atmospheric pressure increases, mercury moves from the short to the long limb, the float falls, and the pointer moves.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] When pressure falls, the mercury moves back, lifting the float and turning the dial the other way.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Around 1810 the wheel barometer, which could be read from a great distance, became the first practical and commercial instrument favoured by farmers and the educated classes in the UK.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The face of the barometer was circular with a simple dial pointing to an easily readable scale: "Rain - Change - Dry" with the "Change" at the top centre of the dial.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Later models added a barometric scale with finer graduations: "Stormy (28 inches of mercury), Much Rain (28.5), Rain (29), Change (29.5), Fair (30), Set fair (30.5), very dry (31)".
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Natalo Aiano is recognised as one of the finest makers of wheel barometers, an early pioneer in a wave of artisanal Italian instrument and barometer makers that were encouraged to emigrate to the UK.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He listed as working in Holborn, London c.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] From 1770 onwards, a large number of Italians came to England because they were accomplished glass blowers or instrument makers.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] By 1840 it was fair to say that the Italians dominated the industry in England.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Using vacuum pump oil as the working fluid in a barometer has led to the creation of the new "World's Tallest Barometer" in February 2013.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The barometer at Portland State University (PSU) uses doubly distilled vacuum pump oil and has a nominal height of about 12.4 m for the oil column height; expected excursions are in the range of ±0.4 m over the course of a year.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Vacuum pump oil has very low vapour pressure and is available in a range of densities; the lowest density vacuum oil was chosen for the PSU barometer to maximize the oil column height.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] An Aneroid barometer is an instrument used for measuring air pressure via a method that does not involve liquid.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Although Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz first proposed the concept of an aneroid barometer around 1700, it was not until 1844 that French scientist Lucien Vidi successfully invented it.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The aneroid barometer uses a small, flexible metal box called an aneroid cell (capsule), which is made from an alloy of beryllium and copper.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The evacuated capsule (or usually several capsules, stacked to add up their movements) is prevented from collapsing by a strong spring.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Small changes in external air pressure cause the cell to expand or contract.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This expansion and contraction drives mechanical levers such that the tiny movements of the capsule are amplified and displayed on the face of the aneroid barometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Many models include a manually set needle which is used to mark the current measurement so that a relative change can be seen.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This type of barometer is common in homes and in recreational boats.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] It is also used in meteorology, mostly in barographs, and as a pressure instrument in radiosondes.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A barograph is a recording aneroid barometer where the changes in atmospheric pressure are recorded on a paper chart.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The principle of the barograph is same as that of the aneroid barometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Whereas the barometer displays the pressure on a dial, the barograph uses the small movements of the box to transmit by a system of levers to a recording arm that has at its extreme end either a scribe or a pen.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A scribe records on smoked foil while a pen records on paper using ink, held in a nib.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The recording material is mounted on a cylindrical drum which is rotated slowly by a clock.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Commonly, the drum makes one revolution per day, per week, or per month, and the rotation rate can often be selected by the user.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Microelectromechanical systems (or MEMS) barometers are extremely small devices between 1 and 100 micrometres in size (0.001 to 0.1 mm).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] They are created via photolithography or photochemical machining.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Typical applications include miniaturized weather stations, electronic barometers and altimeters.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A barometer can also be found in smartphones such as the Samsung Galaxy Nexus, Samsung Galaxy S3-S6, Motorola Xoom, Apple iPhone 6 and newer iPhones, and Timex Expedition WS4 smartwatch, based on MEMS and piezoresistive pressure-sensing technologies.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Inclusion of barometers on smartphones was originally intended to provide a faster GPS lock.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] However, third party researchers were unable to confirm additional GPS accuracy or lock speed due to barometric readings.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The researchers suggest that the inclusion of barometers in smartphones may provide a solution for determining a user's elevation, but also suggest that several pitfalls must first be overcome.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] There are many other more unusual types of barometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] From variations on the storm barometer, such as the Collins Patent Table Barometer, to more traditional-looking designs such as Hooke's Otheometer and the Ross Sympiesometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Some, such as the Shark Oil barometer, work only in a certain temperature range, achieved in warmer climates.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Barometric pressure and the pressure tendency (the change of pressure over time) have been used in weather forecasting since the late 19th century.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] When used in combination with wind observations, reasonably accurate short-term forecasts can be made.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Simultaneous barometric readings from across a network of weather stations allow maps of air pressure to be produced, which were the first form of the modern weather map when created in the 19th century.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Isobars, lines of equal pressure, when drawn on such a map, give a contour map showing areas of high and low pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Localized high atmospheric pressure acts as a barrier to approaching weather systems, diverting their course.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Atmospheric lift caused by low-level wind convergence into the surface brings clouds and sometimes precipitation.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The larger the change in pressure, especially if more than 3.5 hPa (0.1 inHg), the greater the change in weather that can be expected.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] If the pressure drop is rapid, a low pressure system is approaching, and there is a greater chance of rain.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Rapid pressure rises, such as in the wake of a cold front, are associated with improving weather conditions, such as clearing skies.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] With falling air pressure, gases trapped within the coal in deep mines can escape more freely.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Thus low pressure increases the risk of firedamp accumulating.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Collieries therefore keep track of the pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In the case of the Trimdon Grange colliery disaster of 1882 the mines inspector drew attention to the records and in the report stated "the conditions of atmosphere and temperature may be taken to have reached a dangerous point".
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Aneroid barometers are used in scuba diving.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] A submersible pressure gauge is used to keep track of the contents of the diver's air tank.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Another gauge is used to measure the hydrostatic pressure, usually expressed as a depth of sea water.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Either or both gauges may be replaced with electronic variants or a dive computer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The density of mercury depends on temperature, so readings must be adjusted for the temperature of the instrument.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] For this purpose mercury thermometers may be mounted on barometers.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Temperature compensation of an aneroid barometer can be accomplished by including a bi-metal element in the mechanical linkages.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Inexpensive aneroid barometers sold for domestic use typically are manufactured to be accurate at room temperature, and have no provision for further adjustment for temperature.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] As the air pressure decreases at altitudes above sea level (and increases below sea level) the uncorrected reading of the barometer will depend on its location.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The reading is then adjusted to an equivalent sea-level pressure for purposes of reporting.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] For example, if a barometer located at sea level and under fair weather conditions is moved to an altitude of 1,000 feet (305 m), about 1 inch of mercury (~35 hPa) must be added on to the reading.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The barometer readings at the two locations should be the same if there are negligible changes in time, horizontal distance, and temperature.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] If this were not done, there would be a false indication of an approaching storm at the higher elevation.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Aneroid barometers have a mechanical adjustment that allows the equivalent sea level pressure to be read directly and without further adjustment if the instrument is not moved to a different altitude.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Setting an aneroid barometer is similar to resetting an analog clock that is not at the correct time.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Its dial is rotated so that the current atmospheric pressure from a known accurate and nearby barometer (such as the local weather station) is displayed.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] No calculation is needed, as the source barometer reading has already been converted to equivalent sea-level pressure, and this is transferred to the barometer being set—regardless of its altitude.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Though somewhat rare, a few aneroid barometers intended for monitoring the weather are calibrated to manually adjust for altitude.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In this case, knowing *either* the altitude or the current atmospheric pressure would be sufficient for future accurate readings.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The table below shows examples for three locations in the city of San Francisco, California.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Note the corrected barometer readings are identical, and based on equivalent sea-level pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In 1787, during a scientific expedition on Mont Blanc, De Saussure undertook research and executed physical experiments on the boiling point of water at different heights.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] He calculated the height at each of his experiments by measuring how long it took an alcohol burner to boil an amount of water, and by these means he determined the height of the mountain to be 4775 metres.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] (This later turned out to be 32 metres less than the actual height of 4807 metres).
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] For these experiments De Saussure brought specific scientific equipment, such as a barometer and thermometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] His calculated boiling temperature of water at the top of the mountain was fairly accurate, only off by 0.1 kelvin.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Based on his findings, the pressure altimeter was developed as a specific application of the barometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In the mid-19th century, this method was used by explorers.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] When atmospheric pressure is measured by a barometer, the pressure is also referred to as the "barometric pressure".
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] Assume a barometer with a cross-sectional area *A*, a height *h*, filled with mercury from the bottom at Point B to the top at Point C.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The pressure at the bottom of the barometer, Point B, is equal to the atmospheric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The pressure at the very top, Point C, can be taken as zero because there is only mercury vapour above this point and its pressure is very low relative to the atmospheric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] where ρ is the density of mercury, g is the gravitational acceleration, and h is the height of the mercury column above the free surface area.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] The physical dimensions (length of tube and cross-sectional area of the tube) of the barometer itself have no effect on the height of the fluid column in the tube.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] In thermodynamic calculations, a commonly used pressure unit is the "standard atmosphere".
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] This is the pressure resulting from a column of mercury of 760 mm in height at 0 °C.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] For the density of mercury, use ρHg = 13,595 kg/m3 and for gravitational acceleration use g = 9.807 m/s2.
[src:pressure-sensors/barometer] If water were used (instead of mercury) to meet the standard atmospheric pressure, a water column of roughly 10.3 m (33.8 ft) would be needed.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A vacuum gauge is used to measure pressures lower than the ambient atmospheric pressure, which is set as the zero point, in negative values (for instance, −1 bar or −760 mmHg equals total vacuum).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Most gauges measure pressure relative to atmospheric pressure as the zero point, so this form of reading is simply referred to as "gauge pressure".
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] However, anything greater than total vacuum is technically a form of pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For very low pressures, a gauge that uses total vacuum as the zero point reference must be used, giving pressure reading as an absolute pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Other methods of pressure measurement involve sensors that can transmit the pressure reading to a remote indicator or control system (telemetry).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Everyday pressure measurements, such as for vehicle tire pressure, are usually made relative to ambient air pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In other cases measurements are made relative to a vacuum or to some other specific reference.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The zero reference in use is usually implied by context, and these words are added only when clarification is needed.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Tire pressure and blood pressure are gauge pressures by convention, while atmospheric pressures, deep vacuum pressures, and altimeter pressures must be absolute.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For most working fluids where a fluid exists in a closed system, gauge pressure measurement prevails.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Pressure instruments connected to the system will indicate pressures relative to the current atmospheric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The situation changes when extreme vacuum pressures are measured, then absolute pressures are typically used instead and measuring instruments used will be different.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Differential pressures are commonly used in industrial process systems.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Differential pressure gauges have two inlet ports, each connected to one of the volumes whose pressure is to be monitored.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In effect, such a gauge performs the mathematical operation of subtraction through mechanical means, obviating the need for an operator or control system to watch two separate gauges and determine the difference in readings.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Moderate *vacuum pressure* readings can be ambiguous without the proper context, as they may represent absolute pressure or gauge pressure without a negative sign.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Thus a vacuum of 26 inHg gauge is equivalent to an absolute pressure of 4 inHg, calculated as 30 inHg (typical atmospheric pressure) − 26 inHg (gauge pressure).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Atmospheric pressure is typically about 100 kPa at sea level, but is variable with altitude and weather.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] If the absolute pressure of a fluid stays constant, the gauge pressure of the same fluid will vary as atmospheric pressure changes.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For example, when a car drives up a mountain, the (gauge) tire pressure goes up because atmospheric pressure goes down.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The absolute pressure in the tire is essentially unchanged.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Using atmospheric pressure as reference is usually signified by a "g" for gauge after the pressure unit, e.g.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] 70 psig, which means that the pressure measured is the total pressure minus atmospheric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] There are two types of gauge reference pressure: vented gauge (vg) and sealed gauge (sg).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A vented-gauge pressure transmitter, for example, allows the outside air pressure to be exposed to the negative side of the pressure-sensing diaphragm, through a vented cable or a hole on the side of the device, so that it always measures the pressure referred to ambient barometric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Thus a vented-gauge reference pressure sensor should always read zero pressure when the process pressure connection is held open to the air.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A sealed gauge reference is very similar, except that atmospheric pressure is sealed on the negative side of the diaphragm.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This is usually adopted on high pressure ranges, such as hydraulics, where atmospheric pressure changes will have a negligible effect on the accuracy of the reading, so venting is not necessary.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This also allows some manufacturers to provide secondary pressure containment as an extra precaution for pressure equipment safety if the burst pressure of the primary pressure sensing diaphragm is exceeded.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] There is another way of creating a sealed gauge reference, and this is to seal a high vacuum on the reverse side of the sensing diaphragm.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Then the output signal is offset, so the pressure sensor reads close to zero when measuring atmospheric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A sealed gauge reference pressure transducer will never read exactly zero because atmospheric pressure is always changing and the reference in this case is fixed at 1 bar.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] To produce an absolute pressure sensor, the manufacturer seals a high vacuum behind the sensing diaphragm.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] If the process-pressure connection of an absolute-pressure transmitter is open to the air, it will read the actual barometric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A **sealed pressure sensor** is similar to a gauge pressure sensor except that it measures pressure relative to some fixed pressure rather than the ambient atmospheric pressure (which varies according to the location and the weather).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For much of human history, the pressure of gases like air was ignored, denied, or taken for granted, but as early as the 6th century BC, Greek philosopher Anaximenes of Miletus claimed that all things are made of air that is simply changed by varying levels of pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] He could observe water evaporating, changing to a gas, and felt that this applied even to solid matter.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] More condensed air made colder, heavier objects, and expanded air made lighter, hotter objects.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This was akin to how gases really do become less dense when warmer, more dense when cooler.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In the 17th century, Evangelista Torricelli conducted experiments with mercury that allowed him to measure the presence of air.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] He would dip a glass tube, closed at one end, into a bowl of mercury and raise the closed end up out of it, keeping the open end submerged.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The weight of the mercury would pull it down, leaving a partial vacuum at the far end.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This validated his belief that air/gas has mass, creating pressure on things around it.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Previously, the more popular conclusion, even for Galileo, was that air was weightless and it is vacuum that provided force, as in a siphon.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This test, known as Torricelli's experiment, was essentially the first documented pressure gauge.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Blaise Pascal went further, having his brother-in-law try the experiment at different altitudes on a mountain, and finding indeed that the farther down in the ocean of atmosphere, the higher the pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The SI unit for pressure is the pascal (Pa), equal to one newton per square metre (N·m−2 or kg·m−1·s−2).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This special name for the unit was added in 1971; before that, pressure in SI was expressed in units such as N·m−2.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] When indicated, the zero reference is stated in parentheses following the unit, for example 101 kPa (abs).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The pound per square inch (psi) is still in widespread use in the US and Canada, for measuring, for instance, tire pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A letter is often appended to the psi unit to indicate the measurement's zero reference; psia for absolute, psig for gauge, psid for differential, although this practice is discouraged by the NIST.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Because pressure was once commonly measured by its ability to displace a column of liquid in a manometer, pressures are often expressed as a depth of a particular fluid (*e.g.,* inches of water).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Manometric measurement is the subject of pressure head calculations.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The most common choices for a manometer's fluid are mercury (Hg) and water; water is nontoxic and readily available, while mercury's density allows for a shorter column (and so a smaller manometer) to measure a given pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The abbreviation "W.C." or the words "water column" are often printed on gauges and measurements that use water for the manometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Fluid density and local gravity can vary from one reading to another depending on local factors, so the height of a fluid column does not define pressure precisely.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] So measurements in "millimetres of mercury" or "inches of mercury" can be converted to SI units as long as attention is paid to the local factors of fluid density and gravity.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Temperature fluctuations change the value of fluid density, while location can affect gravity.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Although no longer preferred, these **manometric units** are still encountered in many fields.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Blood pressure is measured in millimetres of mercury (see torr) in most of the world, central venous pressure and lung pressures in centimeters of water are still common, as in settings for CPAP machines.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Underwater divers use manometric units: the ambient pressure is measured in units of metres sea water (msw) which is defined as equal to one tenth of a bar.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The unit used in the US is the foot sea water (fsw), based on standard gravity and a sea-water density of 64 lb/ft3.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] According to the US Navy Diving Manual, one fsw equals 0.30643 msw, 0.030643 bar, or 0.44444 psi, though elsewhere it states that 33 fsw is 14.7 psi (one atmosphere), which gives one fsw equal to about 0.445 psi.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The msw and fsw are the conventional units for measurement of diver pressure exposure used in decompression tables and the unit of calibration for pneumofathometers and hyperbaric chamber pressure gauges.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Both msw and fsw are measured relative to normal atmospheric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In vacuum systems, the units torr (millimeter of mercury), micron (micrometer of mercury), and inch of mercury (inHg) are most commonly used.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Torr and micron usually indicates an absolute pressure, while inHg usually indicates a gauge pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Atmospheric pressures are usually stated using hectopascal (hPa), kilopascal (kPa), millibar (mbar) or atmospheres (atm).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In American and Canadian engineering, stress is often measured in kip.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Stress is not a true pressure since it is not scalar.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In the cgs system the unit of pressure was the barye (ba), equal to 1 dyn·cm−2.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In the mts system, the unit of pressure was the pieze, equal to 1 sthene per square metre.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Many other hybrid units are used such as mmHg/cm2 or grams-force/cm2 (sometimes as kg/cm2 without properly identifying the force units).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Using the names kilogram, gram, kilogram-force, or gram-force (or their symbols) as a unit of force is prohibited in SI; the unit of force in SI is the newton (N).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Static pressure is uniform in all directions, so pressure measurements are independent of direction in an immovable (static) fluid.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Flow, however, applies additional pressure on surfaces perpendicular to the flow direction, while having little impact on surfaces parallel to the flow direction.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This directional component of pressure in a moving (dynamic) fluid is called dynamic pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] An instrument facing the flow direction measures the sum of the static and dynamic pressures; this measurement is called the total pressure or stagnation pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Since dynamic pressure is referenced to static pressure, it is neither gauge nor absolute; it is a differential pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] While static gauge pressure is of primary importance to determining net loads on pipe walls, dynamic pressure is used to measure flow rates and airspeed.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Dynamic pressure can be measured by taking the differential pressure between instruments parallel and perpendicular to the flow.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Pitot-static tubes, for example perform this measurement on airplanes to determine airspeed.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The presence of the measuring instrument inevitably acts to divert flow and create turbulence, so its shape is critical to accuracy and the calibration curves are often non-linear.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A **pressure sensor** is a device for pressure measurement of gases or liquids.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Pressure sensors can alternatively be called **pressure transducers**, **pressure transmitters**, **pressure senders**, **pressure indicators**, **piezometers** and **manometers**, among other names.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Pressure is an expression of the force required to stop a fluid from expanding, and is usually stated in terms of force per unit area.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A pressure sensor usually acts as a transducer; it generates a signal as a function of the pressure imposed.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Pressure sensors can vary drastically in technology, design, performance, application suitability and cost.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A conservative estimate would be that there may be over 50 technologies and at least 300 companies making pressure sensors worldwide.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] There is also a category of pressure sensors that are designed to measure in a dynamic mode for capturing very high speed changes in pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Example applications for this type of sensor would be in the measuring of combustion pressure in an engine cylinder or in a gas turbine.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] These sensors are commonly manufactured out of piezoelectric materials such as quartz.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Some pressure sensors are pressure switches, which turn on or off at a particular pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For example, a water pump can be controlled by a pressure switch so that it starts when water is released from the system, reducing the pressure in a reservoir.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Pressure range, sensitivity, dynamic response and cost all vary by several orders of magnitude from one instrument design to the next.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The oldest type is the liquid column manometer (a vertical tube filled with mercury) invented by Evangelista Torricelli in 1643.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The U-Tube was invented by Christiaan Huygens in 1661.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] There are two basic categories of analog pressure sensors: force collector and other types.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] These types of electronic pressure sensors generally use a force collector (such a diaphragm, piston, Bourdon tube, or bellows) to measure strain (or deflection) due to applied force over an area (pressure).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] These types of electronic pressure sensors use other properties (such as density) to infer pressure of a gas, or liquid.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A pressure sensor, a resonant quartz crystal strain gauge with a Bourdon tube force collector, is the critical sensor of DART.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] DART detects tsunami waves from the bottom of the open ocean.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] It has a pressure resolution of approximately 1mm of water when measuring pressure at a depth of several kilometers.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Piston-type gauges counterbalance the pressure of a fluid with a spring (for example tire-pressure gauges of comparatively low accuracy) or a solid weight, in which case it is known as a deadweight tester and may be used for calibration of other gauges.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Liquid-column gauges consist of a column of liquid in a tube whose ends are exposed to different pressures.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The column will rise or fall until its weight (a force applied due to gravity) is in equilibrium with the pressure differential between the two ends of the tube (a force applied due to fluid pressure).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A very simple version is a U-shaped tube half-full of liquid, one side of which is connected to the region of interest while the reference pressure (which might be the atmospheric pressure or a vacuum) is applied to the other.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The difference in liquid levels represents the applied pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The pressure exerted by a column of fluid of height *h* and density *ρ* is given by the hydrostatic pressure equation, *P* = *hgρ*.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Therefore, the pressure difference between the applied pressure *Pa* and the reference pressure *P*0 in a U-tube manometer can be found by solving *Pa* − *P*0 = *hgρ*.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In other words, the pressure on either end of the liquid (shown in blue in the figure) must be balanced (since the liquid is static), and so *Pa* = *P*0 + *hgρ*.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In most liquid-column measurements, the result of the measurement is the height *h*, expressed typically in mm, cm, or inches.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The *h* is also known as the pressure head.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] When expressed as a pressure head, pressure is specified in units of length and the measurement fluid must be specified.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] When accuracy is critical, the temperature of the measurement fluid must likewise be specified, because liquid density is a function of temperature.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] So, for example, pressure head might be written "742.2 mmHg" or "4.2 inH2O at 59 °F" for measurements taken with mercury or water as the manometric fluid respectively.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The word "gauge" or "vacuum" may be added to such a measurement to distinguish between a pressure above or below the atmospheric pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Both mm of mercury and inches of water are common pressure heads, which can be converted to S.I. units of pressure using unit conversion and the above formulas.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Although any fluid can be used, mercury is preferred for its high density (13.534 g/cm3) and low vapour pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For low pressure differences, light oil or water are commonly used (the latter giving rise to units of measurement such as inches water gauge and millimetres H2O).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Liquid-column pressure gauges have a highly linear calibration.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] They have poor dynamic response because the fluid in the column may react slowly to a pressure change.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] One of the disadvantages of the mercury manometer or barometer is that its reading is temperature dependent, a fact made clear by the use of mercury in glass thermometers.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] When measuring vacuum, the working liquid may evaporate and contaminate the vacuum if its vapor pressure is too high.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] When measuring liquid pressure, a loop filled with gas or a light fluid can isolate the liquids to prevent them from mixing, but this can be unnecessary, for example, when mercury is used as the manometer fluid to measure differential pressure of a fluid such as water.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Simple hydrostatic gauges can measure pressures ranging from a few torrs (a few 100 Pa) to a few atmospheres (approximately 1000000 Pa).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A single-limb liquid-column manometer has a larger reservoir instead of one side of the U-tube and has a scale beside the narrower column.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The column may be inclined to further amplify the liquid movement.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A McLeod gauge isolates a sample of gas and compresses it in a modified mercury manometer until the pressure is a few millimetres of mercury.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The technique is very slow and unsuited to continual monitoring, but is capable of good accuracy.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Unlike other manometer gauges, the McLeod gauge reading is dependent on the composition of the gas, since the interpretation relies on the sample compressing as an ideal gas.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Due to the compression process, the McLeod gauge completely ignores partial pressures from non-ideal vapors that condense, such as pump oils, mercury, and even water if compressed enough.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] 0.1 mPa is the lowest direct measurement of pressure that is possible with current technology.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Other vacuum gauges can measure lower pressures, but only indirectly by measurement of other pressure-dependent properties.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] These indirect measurements must be calibrated to SI units by a direct measurement, most commonly a McLeod gauge.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The Bourdon pressure gauge uses the principle that a flattened tube tends to straighten or regain its circular form in cross-section when pressurized.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] (A party horn illustrates this principle.) This change in cross-section may be hardly noticeable, involving moderate stresses within the elastic range of easily workable materials.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The strain of the material of the tube is magnified by forming the tube into a C shape or even a helix, such that the entire tube tends to straighten out or uncoil elastically as it is pressurized.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Eugène Bourdon patented his gauge in France in 1849, and it was widely adopted because of its superior simplicity, linearity, and accuracy; Bourdon is now part of the Baumer group and still manufacture Bourdon tube gauges in France.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Edward Ashcroft purchased Bourdon's American patent rights in 1852 and became a major manufacturer of gauges.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Also in 1849, Bernard Schaeffer in Magdeburg, Germany patented a successful diaphragm (see below) pressure gauge, which, together with the Bourdon gauge, revolutionized pressure measurement in industry.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] But in 1875 after Bourdon's patents expired, his company Schaeffer and Budenberg also manufactured Bourdon tube gauges.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In practice, a flattened thin-wall, closed-end tube is connected at the hollow end to a fixed pipe containing the fluid pressure to be measured.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] As the pressure increases, the closed end moves in an arc, and this motion is converted into the rotation of a (segment of a) gear by a connecting link that is usually adjustable.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A small-diameter pinion gear is on the pointer shaft, so the motion is magnified further by the gear ratio.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The positioning of the indicator card behind the pointer, the initial pointer shaft position, the linkage length and initial position, all provide means to calibrate the pointer to indicate the desired range of pressure for variations in the behavior of the Bourdon tube itself.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Differential pressure can be measured by gauges containing two different Bourdon tubes, with connecting linkages (but is more usually measured via diaphragms or bellows and a balance system).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Bourdon tubes measures gauge pressure, relative to ambient atmospheric pressure, as opposed to absolute pressure; vacuum is sensed as a reverse motion.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Some aneroid barometers use Bourdon tubes closed at both ends (but most use diaphragms or capsules, see below).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Typical high-quality modern gauges provide an accuracy of ±1% of span (Nominal diameter 100mm, Class 1 EN837-1), and a special high-accuracy gauge can be as accurate as 0.1% of full scale.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Due to the extremely stable and repeatable mechanical and thermal properties of quartz and the force balancing which eliminates nearly all physical movement these sensors can be accurate to around 1 PPM of full scale.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Due to the extremely fine fused quartz structures which must be made by hand these sensors are generally limited to scientific and calibration purposes.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In the following illustrations of a compound gauge (vacuum and gauge pressure), the case and window has been removed to show only the dial, pointer and process connection.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Mechanical details include stationary and moving parts.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] It contains bearing holes for the axles.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] It supports the outer ends of the axles.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Posts to join and space the two chassis plates.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] This has a spur gear that engages the sector gear (7) and extends through the face to drive the indicator needle.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Due to the short distance between the lever arm link boss and the pivot pin and the difference between the effective radius of the sector gear and that of the spur gear, any motion of the Bourdon tube is greatly amplified.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A small motion of the tube results in a large motion of the indicator needle.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A second type of aneroid gauge uses deflection of a flexible membrane that separates regions of different pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The amount of deflection is repeatable for known pressures so the pressure can be determined by using calibration.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The deformation of a thin diaphragm is dependent on the difference in pressure between its two faces.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The reference face can be open to atmosphere to measure gauge pressure, open to a second port to measure differential pressure, or can be sealed against a vacuum or other fixed reference pressure to measure absolute pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The deformation can be measured using mechanical, optical or capacitive techniques.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Ceramic and metallic diaphragms are used.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The useful range is above 10−2 Torr (roughly 1 Pa).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For absolute measurements, welded pressure capsules with diaphragms on either side are often used.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In gauges intended to sense small pressures or pressure differences, or require that an absolute pressure be measured, the gear train and needle may be driven by an enclosed and sealed bellows chamber, called an **aneroid**.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] These devices use the sealed chamber as a reference pressure and are driven by the external pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Other sensitive aircraft instruments such as air speed indicators and rate of climb indicators (variometers) have connections both to the internal part of the aneroid chamber and to an external enclosing chamber.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] These gauges use the attraction of two magnets to translate differential pressure into motion of a dial pointer.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] As differential pressure increases, a magnet attached to either a piston or rubber diaphragm moves.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] A rotary magnet that is attached to a pointer then moves in unison.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] To create different pressure ranges, the spring rate can be increased or decreased.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The spinning-rotor gauge works by measuring how a rotating ball is slowed by the viscosity of the gas being measured.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The ball is made of steel and is magnetically levitated inside a steel tube closed at one end and exposed to the gas to be measured at the other.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The ball is brought up to speed (about 2500 or 3800 rad/s), and the deceleration rate is measured after switching off the drive, by electromagnetic transducers.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] The range of the instrument is 5−5 to 102 Pa (103 Pa with less accuracy).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] It is accurate and stable enough to be used as a secondary standard.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] During the last years this type of gauge became much more user friendly and easier to operate.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] In the past the instrument was famous for requiring some skill and knowledge to use correctly.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] For high accuracy measurements various corrections must be applied and the ball must be spun at a pressure well below the intended measurement pressure for five hours before using.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] It is most useful in calibration and research laboratories where high accuracy is required and qualified technicians are available.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] Insulation vacuum monitoring of cryogenic liquids is a well suited application for this system too.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p01] With the inexpensive and long term stable, weldable sensor, that can be separated from the more costly electronics, it is a perfect fit to all static vacuums.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] is generally glued (foil strain gauge) or deposited (thin-film strain gauge) onto a membrane.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Membrane deflection due to pressure causes a resistance change in the strain gauge which can be electronically measured.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] effect of bonded or formed strain gauges to detect strain due to applied pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] silicon pressure sensor chosen for its excellent performance and long-term stability.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] An additional laser-trimmed resistor is included to normalize pressure sensitivity variations by programming the gain of an external differential amplifier.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This provides good sensitivity and long-term stability.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The two ports of the sensor, apply pressure to the same single transducer, please see pressure flow diagram below.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This is an over-simplified diagram, but you can see the fundamental design of the internal ports in the sensor.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The important item here to note is the "diaphragm" as this is the sensor itself.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Is it slightly convex in shape (highly exaggerated in the drawing); this is important as it affects the accuracy of the sensor in use.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The shape of the sensor is important because it is calibrated to work in the direction of air flow as shown by the RED arrows.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This is normal operation for the pressure sensor, providing a positive reading on the display of the digital pressure meter.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Applying pressure in the reverse direction can induce errors in the results as the movement of the air pressure is trying to force the diaphragm to move in the opposite direction.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The errors induced by this are small, but can be significant, and therefore it is always preferable to ensure that the more positive pressure is always applied to the positive (+ve) port and the lower pressure is applied to the negative (-ve) port, for normal 'gauge pressure' application.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The same applies to measuring the difference between two vacuums, the larger vacuum should always be applied to the negative (-ve) port.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The measurement of pressure via the Wheatstone Bridge looks something like this....
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The effective electrical model of the transducer, together with a basic signal conditioning circuit, is shown in the application schematic.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The pressure sensor is a fully active Wheatstone bridge which has been temperature compensated and offset adjusted by means of thick film, laser trimmed resistors.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The excitation to the bridge is applied via a constant current.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The low-level bridge output is at +O and -O, and the amplified span is set by the gain programming resistor (r).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The electrical design is microprocessor controlled, which allows for calibration, the additional functions for the user, such as Scale Selection, Data Hold, Zero and Filter functions, the Record function that stores/displays MAX/MIN.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] to detect strain due to applied pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] effect in certain materials such as quartz to measure the strain upon the sensing mechanism due to pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Uses the physical change of an optical fiber to detect strain due to applied pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Uses the motion of a wiper along a resistive mechanism to detect the strain caused by applied pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] in a sensing mechanism to measure stress, or changes in gas density, caused by applied pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Generally, as a real gas increases in density -which may indicate an increase in pressure- its ability to conduct heat increases.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In this type of gauge, a wire filament is heated by running current through it.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A thermocouple or resistance thermometer (RTD) can then be used to measure the temperature of the filament.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This temperature is dependent on the rate at which the filament loses heat to the surrounding gas, and therefore on the thermal conductivity.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A common variant is the Pirani gauge, which uses a single platinum filament as both the heated element and RTD.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] These gauges are accurate from 10−3 Torr to 10 Torr, but their calibration is sensitive to the chemical composition of the gases being measured.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A Pirani gauge consists of a metal wire open to the pressure being measured.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The wire is heated by a current flowing through it and cooled by the gas surrounding it.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] If the gas pressure is reduced, the cooling effect will decrease, hence the equilibrium temperature of the wire will increase.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The resistance of the wire is a function of its temperature: by measuring the voltage across the wire and the current flowing through it, the resistance (and so the gas pressure) can be determined.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This type of gauge was invented by Marcello Pirani.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In two-wire gauges, one wire coil is used as a heater, and the other is used to measure temperature due to convection.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] **Thermocouple gauges** and **thermistor gauges** work in this manner using a thermocouple or thermistor, respectively, to measure the temperature of the heated wire.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Thermionic emission generates electrons, which collide with gas atoms and generate positive ions.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The ions are attracted to a suitably biased electrode known as the collector.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The current in the collector is proportional to the rate of ionization, which is a function of the pressure in the system.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Hence, measuring the collector current gives the gas pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] There are several sub-types of ionization gauge.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Most ion gauges come in two types: hot cathode and cold cathode.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In the hot cathode version, an electrically heated filament produces an electron beam.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The electrons travel through the gauge and ionize gas molecules around them.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The resulting ions are collected at a negative electrode.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The current depends on the number of ions, which depends on the pressure in the gauge.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Hot cathode gauges are accurate from 10−3 Torr to 10−10 Torr.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The principle behind cold cathode version is the same, except that electrons are produced in the discharge of a high voltage.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Cold cathode gauges are accurate from 10−2 Torr to 10−9 Torr.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Ionization gauge calibration is very sensitive to construction geometry, chemical composition of gases being measured, corrosion and surface deposits.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Their calibration can be invalidated by activation at atmospheric pressure or low vacuum.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The composition of gases at high vacuums will usually be unpredictable, so a mass spectrometer must be used in conjunction with the ionization gauge for accurate measurement.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A hot-cathode ionization gauge is composed mainly of three electrodes acting together as a triode, wherein the cathode is the filament.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The three electrodes are a collector or plate, a filament, and a grid.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The collector current is measured in picoamperes by an electrometer.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The filament voltage to ground is usually at a potential of 30 volts, while the grid voltage at 180–210 volts DC, unless there is an optional electron bombardment feature, by heating the grid, which may have a high potential of approximately 565 volts.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The most common ion gauge is the hot-cathode **Bayard–Alpert gauge**, with a small ion collector inside the grid.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A glass envelope with an opening to the vacuum can surround the electrodes, but usually the **nude gauge** is inserted in the vacuum chamber directly, the pins being fed through a ceramic plate in the wall of the chamber.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Hot-cathode gauges can be damaged or lose their calibration if they are exposed to atmospheric pressure or even low vacuum while hot.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The measurements of a hot-cathode ionization gauge are always logarithmic.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Electrons emitted from the filament move several times in back-and-forth movements around the grid before finally entering the grid.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] During these movements, some electrons collide with a gaseous molecule to form a pair of an ion and an electron (electron ionization).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The number of these ions is proportional to the gaseous molecule density multiplied by the electron current emitted from the filament, and these ions pour into the collector to form an ion current.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Since the gaseous molecule density is proportional to the pressure, the pressure is estimated by measuring the ion current.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The low-pressure sensitivity of hot-cathode gauges is limited by the photoelectric effect.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Electrons hitting the grid produce x-rays that produce photoelectric noise in the ion collector.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This limits the range of older hot-cathode gauges to 10−8 Torr and the Bayard–Alpert to about 10−10 Torr.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Additional wires at cathode potential in the line of sight between the ion collector and the grid prevent this effect.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In the extraction type the ions are not attracted by a wire, but by an open cone.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] As the ions cannot decide which part of the cone to hit, they pass through the hole and form an ion beam.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] There are two subtypes of cold-cathode ionization gauges: the **Penning gauge** (invented by Frans Michel Penning), and the **inverted magnetron**, also called a **Redhead gauge**.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The major difference between the two is the position of the anode with respect to the cathode.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Neither has a filament, and each may require a DC potential of about 4 kV for operation.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Inverted magnetrons can measure down to 1×10−12 Torr.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In ambient air, suitable ion-pairs are ubiquitously formed by cosmic radiation; in a Penning gauge, design features are used to ease the set-up of a discharge path.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] For example, the electrode of a Penning gauge is usually finely tapered to facilitate the field emission of electrons.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Maintenance cycles of cold cathode gauges are, in general, measured in years, depending on the gas type and pressure that they are operated in.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Using a cold cathode gauge in gases with substantial organic components, such as pump oil fractions, can result in the growth of delicate carbon films and shards within the gauge that eventually either short-circuit the electrodes of the gauge or impede the generation of a discharge path.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] When fluid flows are not in equilibrium, local pressures may be higher or lower than the average pressure in a medium.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] These disturbances propagate from their source as longitudinal pressure variations along the path of propagation.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Sound pressure is the instantaneous local pressure deviation from the average pressure caused by a sound wave.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Sound pressure can be measured using a microphone in air and a hydrophone in water.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The effective sound pressure is the root mean square of the instantaneous sound pressure over a given interval of time.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Sound pressures are normally small and are often expressed in units of microbar.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) has developed two separate and distinct standards on pressure measurement, B40.100 and PTC 19.2.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] B40.100 provides guidelines on Pressure Indicated Dial Type and Pressure Digital Indicating Gauges, Diaphragm Seals, Snubbers, and Pressure Limiter Valves.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] PTC 19.2 provides instructions and guidance for the accurate determination of pressure values in support of the ASME Performance Test Codes.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The choice of method, instruments, required calculations, and corrections to be applied depends on the purpose of the measurement, the allowable uncertainty, and the characteristics of the equipment being tested.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The methods for pressure measurement and the protocols used for data transmission are also provided.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Guidance is given for setting up the instrumentation and determining the uncertainty of the measurement.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Information regarding the instrument type, design, applicable pressure range, accuracy, output, and relative cost is provided.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Information is also provided on pressure-measuring devices that are used in field environments i.e., piston gauges, manometers, and low-absolute-pressure (vacuum) instruments.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] These methods are designed to assist in the evaluation of measurement uncertainty based on current technology and engineering knowledge, taking into account published instrumentation specifications and measurement and application techniques.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This Supplement provides guidance in the use of methods to establish the pressure-measurement uncertainty.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This is where the measurement of interest is pressure, expressed as a force per unit area.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This is useful in weather instrumentation, aircraft, automobiles, and any other machinery that has pressure functionality implemented.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This is useful in aircraft, rockets, satellites, weather balloons, and many other applications.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] All these applications make use of the relationship between changes in pressure relative to the altitude.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Outside that range, an error will be introduced which can be calculated differently for each different pressure sensor.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] These error calculations will factor in the error introduced by the change in temperature as we go up.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Barometric pressure sensors can have an altitude resolution of less than 1 meter, which is significantly better than GPS systems (about 20 meters altitude resolution).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In navigation applications altimeters are used to distinguish between stacked road levels for car navigation and floor levels in buildings for pedestrian navigation.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This is the use of pressure sensors in conjunction with the venturi effect to measure flow.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Differential pressure is measured between two segments of a venturi tube that have a different aperture.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The pressure difference between the two segments is directly proportional to the flow rate through the venturi tube.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A low pressure sensor is almost always required as the pressure difference is relatively small.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A pressure sensor may also be used to calculate the level of a fluid.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This technique is commonly employed to measure the depth of a submerged body (such as a diver or submarine), or level of contents in a tank (such as in a water tower).
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] For most practical purposes, fluid level is directly proportional to pressure.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In the case of fresh water where the contents are under atmospheric pressure, 1psi = 27.7 inH2O / 1Pa = 9.81 mmH2O.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A pressure sensor may be used to sense the decay of pressure due to a system leak.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] This is commonly done by either comparison to a known leak using differential pressure, or by means of utilizing the pressure sensor to measure pressure change over time.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A **piezometer** is either a device used to measure liquid pressure in a system by measuring the height to which a column of the liquid rises against gravity, or a device which measures the pressure (more precisely, the piezometric head) of groundwater at a specific point.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A piezometer is designed to measure static pressures, and thus differs from a pitot tube by not being pointed into the fluid flow.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Observation wells give some information on the water level in a formation, but must be read manually.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Electrical pressure transducers of several types can be read automatically, making data acquisition more convenient.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The first piezometers in geotechnical engineering were open wells or standpipes (sometimes called **Casagrande piezometers**) installed into an aquifer.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] A Casagrande piezometer will typically have a solid casing down to the depth of interest, and a slotted or screened casing within the zone where water pressure is being measured.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The casing is sealed into the drillhole with clay, bentonite or concrete to prevent surface water from contaminating the groundwater supply.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In an unconfined aquifer, the water level in the piezometer would not be exactly coincident with the water table, especially when the vertical component of flow velocity is significant.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] In a confined aquifer under artesian conditions, the water level in the piezometer indicates the pressure in the aquifer, but not necessarily the water table.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Piezometer wells can be much smaller in diameter than production wells, and a 5 cm diameter standpipe is common.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] Piezometers in durable casings can be buried or pushed into the ground to measure the groundwater pressure at the point of installation.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] The pressure gauges (transducer) can be vibrating-wire, pneumatic, or strain-gauge in operation, converting pressure into an electrical signal.
[src:pressure-sensors/bourdon-tube-p02] These piezometers are cabled to the surface where they can be read by data loggers or portable readout units, allowing faster or more frequent reading than is possible with open standpipe piezometers.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The **piezoresistive effect** is a change in the electrical resistivity of a semiconductor or metal when mechanical strain is applied.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] In contrast to the piezoelectric effect, the piezoresistive effect causes a change only in electrical resistance, not in electric potential.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The change of electrical resistance in metal devices due to an applied mechanical load was first discovered in 1856 by Lord Kelvin.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] With single crystal silicon becoming the material of choice for the design of analog and digital circuits, the large piezoresistive effect in silicon and germanium was first discovered in 1954 (Smith 1954).
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] In conducting and semi-conducting materials, changes in inter-atomic spacing resulting from strain affect the bandgaps, making it easier (or harder depending on the material and strain) for electrons to be raised into the conduction band.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] This results in a change in resistivity of the material.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Usually the resistance change in metals is mostly due to the change of geometry resulting from applied mechanical stress.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] However, even though the piezoresistive effect is small in those cases it is often not negligible.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Some metals display piezoresistivity that is much larger than the resistance change due to geometry.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] In platinum alloys, for instance, piezoresistivity is more than a factor of two larger, combining with the geometry effects to give a strain gauge sensitivity of up to more than three times as large than due to geometry effects alone.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Pure nickel's piezoresistivity is -13 times larger, completely dwarfing and even reversing the sign of the geometry-induced resistance change.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The piezoresistive effect of semiconductor materials can be several orders of magnitudes larger than the geometrical effect and is present in materials like germanium, polycrystalline silicon, amorphous silicon, silicon carbide, and single crystal silicon.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Hence, semiconductor strain gauges with a very high coefficient of sensitivity can be built.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] For precision measurements they are more difficult to handle than metal strain gauges, because semiconductor strain gauges are generally sensitive to environmental conditions (especially temperature).
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] For silicon, gauge factors can be two orders of magnitudes larger than those observed in most metals (Smith 1954).
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The resistance of n-conducting silicon mainly changes due to a shift of the three different conducting valley pairs.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The shifting causes a redistribution of the carriers between valleys with different mobilities.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] This results in varying mobilities dependent on the direction of current flow.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] A minor effect is due to the effective mass change related to changing shapes of the valleys.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] In p-conducting silicon the phenomena are more complex and also result in mass changes and hole transfer.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] A giant piezoresistive effect – where the piezoresistive coefficient exceeds the bulk value – was reported for a microfabricated silicon-aluminium hybrid structure.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The effect has been applied to silicon-based sensor technologies.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The longitudinal piezoresistive coefficient of top-down fabricated silicon nanowires was measured to be 60% larger than in bulk silicon.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] In 2006, giant piezoresistance was reported in bottom-up fabricated silicon nanowires – a >30 increase in the longitudinal piezoresistive coefficient compared to bulk silicon was reported.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The suggestion of a giant piezoresistance in nanostructures has since stimulated much effort into a physical understanding of the effect not only in silicon but also in other functional materials.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The piezoresistive effect of semiconductors has been used for sensor devices employing all kinds of semiconductor materials such as germanium, polycrystalline silicon, amorphous silicon, and single crystal silicon.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Since silicon is today the material of choice for integrated digital and analog circuits the use of piezoresistive silicon devices has been of great interest.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] It enables the easy integration of stress sensors with Bipolar and CMOS circuits.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] This has enabled a wide range of products using the piezoresistive effect.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Many commercial devices such as pressure sensors and acceleration sensors employ the piezoresistive effect in silicon.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] But due to its magnitude the piezoresistive effect in silicon has also attracted the attention of research and development for all other devices using single crystal silicon.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Semiconductor Hall sensors, for example, were capable of achieving their current precision only after employing methods which eliminate signal contributions due to applied mechanical stress.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Piezoresistors are resistors made from a piezoresistive material and are usually used for measurement of mechanical stress.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] They are the simplest form of piezoresistive devices.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] For typical stress values in the MPa range the stress dependent voltage drop along the resistor Vr, can be considered to be linear.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] where $R_{0}$ , *I*, $\pi _{T}$ , $\pi _{L}$ , and $\sigma _{ij}$ denote the stress free resistance, the applied current, the transverse and longitudinal piezoresistive coefficients, and the three tensile stress components, respectively.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The piezoresistive coefficients vary significantly with the sensor orientation with respect to the crystallographic axes and with the doping profile.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Despite the fairly large stress sensitivity of simple resistors, they are preferably used in more complex configurations eliminating certain cross sensitivities and drawbacks.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] Piezoresistors have the disadvantage of being highly sensitive to temperature changes while featuring comparatively small relative stress dependent signal amplitude changes.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] In silicon the piezoresistive effect is used in piezoresistors, transducers, piezo-FETS, solid state accelerometers and bipolar transistors.
[src:pressure-sensors/piezoresistive-effect] The electrically-conductive packaging material Velostat is used by hobbyists to make pressure sensors due to its piezoresistive properties and low cost.
